I do, I think we have to be skeptical.

30
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:25,000
I think the track record for economists and other social scientists isn't good.

31
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:28,000
When we look, you know, for hundreds of years, a hundred years now,

32
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:32,000
people have been predicting that there will be really quite dramatic reductions in working time

33
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,000
like Elon Musk has just made.

34
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:39,000
And previously, those predictions, although we're heading very gradually in that direction,

35
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:46,000
those predictions of very, very large changes in working time just haven't come to pass.

36
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:51,000
Sean asks if we should take predictions with a pinch of salt.

37
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:56,000
To take something with a pinch of salt is an idiom, meaning to doubt

38
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:01,000
that what you've been told is accurate or likely to come true.

39
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:07,000
For example, if your friend always lies, you take what they say with a pinch of salt.

40
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Professor Birchall thinks predictions for the future of work have a bad track record.

41
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:19,000
A track record means all the achievements or failures that someone has had in the past.

42
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:25,000
When it comes to predicting the future of work, most predictions simply haven't come to pass,

43
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,000
an old fashioned way of saying happened will come true.

44
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:36,000
So are predictions for a future of leisure relaxing by the pool while robots do all the work

45
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
just a dream.

46
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Let's hear from Andrew Palmer, business editor for the Economist magazine,

47
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
talking to BBC World Service Program, The Real Story.

48
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,000
I'm not a tech dystopian.

49
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,000
I don't think that machines or AI are going to get rid of all jobs.

50
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,000
But I do worry about a sequencing risk.

51
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:59,000
So there will be some disruption from AI, some jobs, some professions are at risk.

52
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,000
And although economists like to say new jobs will crop up,

53
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
they won't necessarily be aligned at the same time.

54
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,000
They won't be coordination.

55
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,000
Andrew is not a dystopian.

56
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Someone who imagines a nightmare future of suffering and injustice.

57
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
He doesn't think AI will get rid of all jobs.

58
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:22,000
To get rid of something means to remove it because you no longer want it.

59
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Andrew predicts that AI will replace some jobs,

60
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,000
and those workers will need support.

61
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,000
But he also thinks new jobs will crop up.

62
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
They will appear unexpectedly.

63
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
And that's exactly the problem.

64
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,000
The future is hard to predict because it's so unexpected.

65
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:44,000
Anyway, I reckon a shorter working week is something we can all agree on right now?

66
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:46,000
Absolutely.

67
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,000
I think it's time to reveal the answer to my question

68
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:54,000
about the 60 companies trying out a shorter working week in 2023.

69
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:59,000
I asked how many of them plan to continue a four-day week at the end of the trials.

70
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
And I guessed 52% so was I right?

71
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
That was the wrong answer I'm afraid, bet.

72
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Actually, a whopping 92% of the companies plan on keeping a four-day week

73
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:14,000
